  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Monday Morg 1/2 past 9 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest W. I am going to the Hen, &amp; shall set out just about 11 o'clock, hoping to see the Guard turn out again.</p>
      <p>You will see in the Examiner the sad account of poor Laut Carpenter's death. Mr Madge noticed it yesterday in his sermon,</p>
      <p>&amp; seemed much affected. I thought he would quite have broken down.--</p>
      <p>Yesterday Miss Murray called in the afternoon, full of enthusiasm about everything &amp; particularly her children. She desired me to send you the enclosed paper of propositions to Government, for your consideration.--</p>
      <p>This evening Mrs Nightingale has asked me to look in,-- only by</p>
      <p>way of calling on her, which I think I shall do.</p>
      <p>Miss Doyle came yesterday evening &amp; was very agreeable indeed, &amp; not dogmatic. She talked much about the E. . Mrs. E. N is likely to add to the family by &amp; bye.--</p>
      <p>Mr Phillott was here yesterday &amp; spoke to me about Charlotte, whom he thinks in danger of falling into very bad health unless she is more careful about herself.</p>
      <p>He says she has been originally inspired by your Mother's strange systems &amp; want of systems.--</p>
      <p>On Satdy as I was riding home through the St James' Park, William Pinney met me &amp; rode home with me, questioning me exceedingly about your sisters, which amused me much.--</p>
      <p>I am expecting the little musical boys.--</p>
      <p>Avis</p>
    </div></body>
